From the two data analysis, we see a sudden increase in Deaths in US from 47 deaths in march 13th 2020, to 194,071 deaths in September 13th, 2020. It moved from 7th highest country to 1st in the list of most deaths. Similarly, Brazil and India also had extreme increase in death tolls as it categorized as 2nd and 3rd highest death tolls respectively. Overall, the list of highest deaths increased by a lot within 6 months - from approximately 10 - 3200 to approximately 23,000 to 194,000.

library(tidyverse)

#03/12/2020

report_03_12_2020 <-   read_csv(url("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_daily_reports/03-12-2020.csv")) 
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   `Province/State` = col_character(),
##   `Country/Region` = col_character(),
##   `Last Update` = col_datetime(format = ""),
##   Confirmed = col_double(),
##   Deaths = col_double(),
##   Recovered = col_double(),
##   Latitude = col_double(),
##   Longitude = col_double()
## )

5. 10 countries with deaths in 03/12/2020

deaths_top10_report_03_12_2020 <- report_03_12_2020 %>% 
  group_by(`Country/Region`) %>% 
  summarize(Deaths = sum(Deaths)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Deaths)) %>% 
  slice(1:10)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
deaths_top10_report_03_12_2020
## # A tibble: 10 x 2
##    `Country/Region` Deaths
##    <chr>             <dbl>
##  1 China              3172
##  2 Italy               827
##  3 Iran                429
##  4 Korea, South         66
##  5 Spain                55
##  6 France               48
##  7 US                   40
##  8 Japan                16
##  9 Iraq                  8
## 10 United Kingdom        8
deaths_top10_report_03_12_2020 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x= `Country/Region`, y =Deaths)) + 
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, aes(color = "red")) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  ggtitle("Top 10 Countries with Deaths in 03/12/2020")

5. 10 countries with Confirmed in 03/12/2020

confirmed_top10_report_03_12_2020 <- report_03_12_2020 %>% 
  group_by(`Country/Region`) %>% 
  summarize(Confirmed = sum(Confirmed)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Confirmed)) %>% 
  slice(1:10)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
